AB  - Three variants of Friedman's consumption model are analyzed using Houthakker's international consumption and income data and the Bayesian Regression Analysis Program (BRAP). The analysis is focussed on evaluating Friedman's proportionality hypothesis. Various diagnostic procedures are discussed and applied using diffuse and informative prior distributions. Of the three models considered, the logit transformation model is deemed most appropriate and results based on it suggest a departure from the proportionality hypothesis, particularlyat low levels of income. This result is at variance with Houthakker's earlier conclusion that these data are in accord with the proportionality hypothesis.
ER  - 

